Overall, by the end of the course, students will be equipped with the knowledge, skills, and competencies to analyze health-related issues within a cultural context critically, conduct original research using anthropological methods, and contribute to developing culturally responsive healthcare practices and policies.Objectives/eesmärkid:  This course offers a hands-on exploration of medical anthropology, emphasizing the application of anthropological theories and methods to study health, illness, and healing practices in diverse cultural contexts. Through lectures, discussions, readings, and case studies, students will develop a nuanced understanding of how social, cultural, and environmental factors shape health outcomes and healthcare systems worldwide. The course culminates in a practical case study project where students will conduct original research, applying anthropological approaches to investigate a specific health-related issue within a cultural context.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Throughout the Practical Medical Anthropology course, students are expected to acquire a range of skills and competencies that will enable them to critically analyze and engage with health-related issues from a cross-cultural perspective. Following skills Cultural Competency: Students will develop an understanding of diverse cultural beliefs, practices, and perspectives related to health and illness, enabling them to navigate and communicate effectively across cultural boundaries. Analytical Thinking: Through exposure to anthropological theories and methods, students will critically analyze the social, cultural, economic, and political factors that shape health outcomes and healthcare systems, fostering a nuanced understanding of complex health issues. Research Skills: Students will acquire practical research skills, including ethnographic research methods such as participant observation, interviewing, and data analysis, preparing them to conduct original research in healthcare settings. Interdisciplinary Perspective: By exploring the intersections between anthropology, sociology, public health, and other disciplines, students will develop an interdisciplinary approach to understanding health and healing, recognizing the interconnectedness of social, cultural, and biological factors. Communication Skills: Through class discussions, presentations, and written assignments, students will enhance their ability to articulate their ideas clearly and persuasively, both orally and in writing. Ethical Awareness: Students will gain an understanding of ethical considerations in medical anthropology research, including issues of informed consent, confidentiality, and cultural sensitivity, enabling them to conduct research ethically and responsibly.
